icials tried to prevent the disease from entering the country by implementing a maritime quarantine, as had been their standard practice since the cholera epidemics of 1832. But the 1918 flu was a different type of disease. In spite of the best efforts of both federal and local officials, up to fifty thousand Canadians died.In The Last Plague, Mark Osborne Humphries examines how federal epidemic disease management strategies developed before the First World War, arguing that the deadliest epidemic in Canadian history ultimately challenged traditional ideas about disease and public health governance. Using federal, provincial, and municipal archival sources, newspapers, and newly discovered military records – as well as original epidemiological studies – Humphries&apos; sweeping national study situates the flu within a larger social, political, and military context for the first time. His provocative conclusion is that the 1918 flu crisis had important long-term consequences at the national level, ushering in the ‘modern’ era of public health in Canada.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aDisease managementzCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 0aDisease management. 0aInfluenza Epidemic, 1918-1919xSocial aspectszCanada. 0aInfluenza Epidemic, 1918-1919zCanadaxHistory. 0aInfluenza. 0aMedical policyzCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 0aPublic healthxPolitical aspectszCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 0aWorld War, 1914-1918xHealth aspectszCanada. 7aHISTORY / Canada / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311049095440uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144268662540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442686625423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781442686625/original  a978-3-11-049095-4  University of Toron